Return S centered in a string of length width. Padding is

children.name: center

Return the number of non-overlapping occurrences of substring sub in
string S[start:end].  Optional arguments start and end are interpreted
as in slice notation.
children.name: count

children.docstring:
S.decode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Decodes S using the codec registered for encoding. encoding defaults
to the default encoding. errors may be given to set a different error
handling scheme. Default is 'strict' meaning that encoding errors raise
a UnicodeDecodeError. Other possible values are 'ignore' and 'replace'
as well as any other name registered with codecs.register_error that is
able to handle UnicodeDecodeErrors.
children.name: decode

children.docstring:
S.encode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Encodes S using the codec registered for encoding. encoding defaults
to the default encoding. errors may be given to set a different error
handling scheme. Default is 'strict' meaning that encoding errors raise
a UnicodeEncodeError. Other possible values are 'ignore', 'replace' and
'xmlcharrefreplace' as well as any other name registered with
codecs.register_error that is able to handle UnicodeEncodeErrors.
children.name: encode

children.docstring:
S.endswith(suffix[, start[, end]]) -> bool

Return True if S ends with the specified suffix, False otherwise.
With optional start, test S beginning at that position.
With optional end, stop comparing S at that position.
suffix can also be a tuple of strings to try.
children.name: endswith

children.docstring:
S.expandtabs([tabsize]) -> string

Return a copy of S where all tab characters are expanded using spaces.
If tabsize is not given, a tab size of 8 characters is assumed.
children.name: expandtabs

children.docstring:

Return the lowest index in S where substring sub is found,
such that sub is contained within S[start:end].  Optional
arguments start and end are interpreted as in slice notation.

Return -1 on failure.
children.name: find

children.docstring:

Return a formatted version of S, using substitutions from args and kwargs.
The substitutions are identified by braces ('{' and '}').

Like S.find() but raise ValueError when the substring is not found.
children.name: index

and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isalnum

Return True if all characters in S are alphabetic
and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isalpha

Return True if all characters in S are digits
and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isdigit

Return True if all cased characters in S are lowercase and there is

children.name: islower

Return True if all characters in S are whitespace
and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isspace

Return True if S is a titlecased string and there is at least one
character in S, i.e. uppercase characters may only follow uncased
characters and lowercase characters only cased ones. Return False
otherwise.

the separator itself, and the part after it.  If the separator is not
found, return S and two empty strings.

old replaced by new.  If the optional argument count is
given, only the first count occurrences are replaced.

arguments start and end are interpreted as in slice notation.

separator is not found, return two empty strings and S.
children.name: rpartition

Return a list of the words in the string S, using sep as the
delimiter string, starting at the end of the string and working
to the front.  If maxsplit is given, at most maxsplit splits are
done. If sep is not specified or is None, any whitespace string
is a separator.
children.name: rsplit

If chars is given and not None, remove characters in chars instead.
If chars is unicode, S will be converted to unicode before stripping
children.name: rstrip

children.docstring:
S.split([sep [,maxsplit]]) -> list of strings

Return a list of the words in the string S, using sep as the
delimiter string.  If maxsplit is given, at most maxsplit
splits are done. If sep is not specified or is None, any
whitespace string is a separator and empty strings are removed
from the result.
children.name: split

children.docstring:
S.splitlines([keepends]) -> list of strings

Return a list of the lines in S, breaking at line boundaries.
Line breaks are not included in the resulting list unless keepends
is given and true.
children.name: splitlines

prefix can also be a tuple of strings to try.
children.name: startswith

children.docstring:

whitespace removed.
If chars is given and not None, remove characters in chars instead.
If chars is unicode, S will be converted to unicode before stripping

in the optional argument deletechars are removed, and the
remaining characters have been mapped through the given
translation table, which must be a string of length 256 or None.
If the table argument is None, no translation is applied and
the operation simply removes the characters in deletechars.

str(object) -> string

Return a nice string representation of the object.
If the argument is a string, the return value is the same object.
children.name: func_name

children.docstring:
S.capitalize() -> string

Return a copy of the string S with only its first character
capitalized.
children.name: capitalize

children.docstring:
S.center(width[, fillchar]) -> string

Return S centered in a string of length width. Padding is
done using the specified fill character (default is a space)
children.name: center

children.docstring:
S.count(sub[, start[, end]]) -> int

Return the number of non-overlapping occurrences of substring sub in
string S[start:end].  Optional arguments start and end are interpreted
as in slice notation.
children.name: count

children.docstring:
S.decode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Decodes S using the codec registered for encoding. encoding defaults
to the default encoding. errors may be given to set a different error
handling scheme. Default is 'strict' meaning that encoding errors raise
a UnicodeDecodeError. Other possible values are 'ignore' and 'replace'
as well as any other name registered with codecs.register_error that is
able to handle UnicodeDecodeErrors.
children.name: decode

children.docstring:
S.encode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Encodes S using the codec registered for encoding. encoding defaults
to the default encoding. errors may be given to set a different error
handling scheme. Default is 'strict' meaning that encoding errors raise
a UnicodeEncodeError. Other possible values are 'ignore', 'replace' and
'xmlcharrefreplace' as well as any other name registered with
codecs.register_error that is able to handle UnicodeEncodeErrors.
children.name: encode

children.docstring:
S.endswith(suffix[, start[, end]]) -> bool

Return True if S ends with the specified suffix, False otherwise.
With optional start, test S beginning at that position.
With optional end, stop comparing S at that position.
suffix can also be a tuple of strings to try.
children.name: endswith

children.docstring:
S.expandtabs([tabsize]) -> string

Return a copy of S where all tab characters are expanded using spaces.
If tabsize is not given, a tab size of 8 characters is assumed.
children.name: expandtabs

children.docstring:
S.find(sub [,start [,end]]) -> int

Return the lowest index in S where substring sub is found,
such that sub is contained within S[start:end].  Optional
arguments start and end are interpreted as in slice notation.

Return -1 on failure.
children.name: find

children.docstring:
S.format(*args, **kwargs) -> string

Return a formatted version of S, using substitutions from args and kwargs.
The substitutions are identified by braces ('{' and '}').
children.name: format

children.docstring:
S.index(sub [,start [,end]]) -> int

Like S.find() but raise ValueError when the substring is not found.
children.name: index

children.docstring:
S.isalnum() -> bool

Return True if all characters in S are alphanumeric
and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isalnum

children.docstring:
S.isalpha() -> bool

Return True if all characters in S are alphabetic
and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isalpha

children.docstring:
S.isdigit() -> bool

Return True if all characters in S are digits
and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isdigit

children.docstring:
S.islower() -> bool

Return True if all cased characters in S are lowercase and there is
at least one cased character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: islower

children.docstring:
S.isspace() -> bool

Return True if all characters in S are whitespace
and there is at least one character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isspace

children.docstring:
S.istitle() -> bool

Return True if S is a titlecased string and there is at least one
character in S, i.e. uppercase characters may only follow uncased
characters and lowercase characters only cased ones. Return False
otherwise.
children.name: istitle

children.docstring:
S.isupper() -> bool

Return True if all cased characters in S are uppercase and there is
at least one cased character in S, False otherwise.
children.name: isupper

children.docstring:
S.join(iterable) -> string

Return a string which is the concatenation of the strings in the
iterable.  The separator between elements is S.
children.name: join

children.docstring:
S.ljust(width[, fillchar]) -> string

Return S left-justified in a string of length width. Padding is
done using the specified fill character (default is a space).
children.name: ljust

children.docstring:
S.lower() -> string

Return a copy of the string S converted to lowercase.
children.name: lower

children.docstring:
S.lstrip([chars]) -> string or unicode

Return a copy of the string S with leading whitespace removed.
If chars is given and not None, remove characters in chars instead.
If chars is unicode, S will be converted to unicode before stripping
children.name: lstrip

children.docstring:
S.partition(sep) -> (head, sep, tail)

Search for the separator sep in S, and return the part before it,
the separator itself, and the part after it.  If the separator is not
found, return S and two empty strings.
children.name: partition

children.docstring:
S.replace(old, new[, count]) -> string

Return a copy of string S with all occurrences of substring
old replaced by new.  If the optional argument count is
given, only the first count occurrences are replaced.
children.name: replace

children.docstring:
S.rfind(sub [,start [,end]]) -> int

Return the highest index in S where substring sub is found,
such that sub is contained within S[start:end].  Optional
arguments start and end are interpreted as in slice notation.

Return -1 on failure.
children.name: rfind

children.docstring:
S.rindex(sub [,start [,end]]) -> int

Like S.rfind() but raise ValueError when the substring is not found.
children.name: rindex

children.docstring:
S.rjust(width[, fillchar]) -> string

Return S right-justified in a string of length width. Padding is
done using the specified fill character (default is a space)
children.name: rjust

children.docstring:
S.rpartition(sep) -> (head, sep, tail)

Search for the separator sep in S, starting at the end of S, and return
the part before it, the separator itself, and the part after it.  If the
separator is not found, return two empty strings and S.
children.name: rpartition

children.docstring:
S.rsplit([sep [,maxsplit]]) -> list of strings

Return a list of the words in the string S, using sep as the
delimiter string, starting at the end of the string and working
to the front.  If maxsplit is given, at most maxsplit splits are
done. If sep is not specified or is None, any whitespace string
is a separator.
children.name: rsplit

children.docstring:
S.rstrip([chars]) -> string or unicode

Return a copy of the string S with trailing whitespace removed.
If chars is given and not None, remove characters in chars instead.
If chars is unicode, S will be converted to unicode before stripping
children.name: rstrip

children.docstring:
S.split([sep [,maxsplit]]) -> list of strings

Return a list of the words in the string S, using sep as the
delimiter string.  If maxsplit is given, at most maxsplit
splits are done. If sep is not specified or is None, any
whitespace string is a separator and empty strings are removed
from the result.
children.name: split

children.docstring:
S.splitlines([keepends]) -> list of strings

Return a list of the lines in S, breaking at line boundaries.
Line breaks are not included in the resulting list unless keepends
is given and true.
children.name: splitlines

children.docstring:
S.startswith(prefix[, start[, end]]) -> bool

Return True if S starts with the specified prefix, False otherwise.
With optional start, test S beginning at that position.
With optional end, stop comparing S at that position.
prefix can also be a tuple of strings to try.
children.name: startswith

children.docstring:
S.strip([chars]) -> string or unicode

Return a copy of the string S with leading and trailing
whitespace removed.
If chars is given and not None, remove characters in chars instead.
If chars is unicode, S will be converted to unicode before stripping
children.name: strip

children.docstring:
S.swapcase() -> string

Return a copy of the string S with uppercase characters
converted to lowercase and vice versa.
children.name: swapcase

children.docstring:
S.title() -> string

Return a titlecased version of S, i.e. words start with uppercase
characters, all remaining cased characters have lowercase.
children.name: title

children.docstring:
S.translate(table [,deletechars]) -> string

Return a copy of the string S, where all characters occurring
in the optional argument deletechars are removed, and the
remaining characters have been mapped through the given
translation table, which must be a string of length 256 or None.
If the table argument is None, no translation is applied and
the operation simply removes the characters in deletechars.
children.name: translate

children.docstring:
S.upper() -> string

Return a copy of the string S converted to uppercase.
children.name: upper

children.docstring:
S.zfill(width) -> string

Pad a numeric string S with zeros on the left, to fill a field
of the specified width.  The string S is never truncated.
children.name: zfill

children.docstring:
This module is always available.  It provides access to the
mathematical functions defined by the C standard.
children.name: math

children.docstring:
acos(x)

Return the arc cosine (measured in radians) of x.
children.name: acos

children.docstring:
acosh(x)

Return the hyperbolic arc cosine (measured in radians) of x.
children.name: acosh

children.docstring:
asin(x)

Return the arc sine (measured in radians) of x.
children.name: asin

children.docstring:
asinh(x)

Return the hyperbolic arc sine (measured in radians) of x.
children.name: asinh

children.docstring:
atan(x)

Return the arc tangent (measured in radians) of x.
children.name: atan

children.docstring:
atan2(y, x)

Return the arc tangent (measured in radians) of y/x.
Unlike atan(y/x), the signs of both x and y are considered.
children.name: atan2

children.docstring:
atanh(x)

Return the hyperbolic arc tangent (measured in radians) of x.
children.name: atanh

children.docstring:
ceil(x)

Return the ceiling of x as a float.
This is the smallest integral value >= x.
children.name: ceil

children.docstring:
copysign(x, y)

Return x with the sign of y.
children.name: copysign

children.docstring:
cos(x)

Return the cosine of x (measured in radians).
children.name: cos

children.docstring:
cosh(x)

Return the hyperbolic cosine of x.
children.name: cosh

children.docstring:
degrees(x)

Convert angle x from radians to degrees.
children.name: degrees

children.docstring:
float(x) -> floating point number

Convert a string or number to a floating point number, if possible.
children.name: e

children.docstring:
erfc(x)

Complementary error function at x.
children.name: erfc

children.docstring:
exp(x)

Return e raised to the power of x.
children.name: exp

children.docstring:
expm1(x)

Return exp(x)-1.
This function avoids the loss of precision involved in the direct evaluation of exp(x)-1 for small x.
children.name: expm1

children.docstring:
fabs(x)

Return the absolute value of the float x.
children.name: fabs

children.docstring:
factorial(x) -> Integral

Find x!. Raise a ValueError if x is negative or non-integral.
children.name: factorial

children.docstring:
floor(x)

Return the floor of x as a float.
This is the largest integral value <= x.
children.name: floor

children.docstring:
fmod(x, y)

Return fmod(x, y), according to platform C.  x % y may differ.
children.name: fmod

children.docstring:
frexp(x)

Return the mantissa and exponent of x, as pair (m, e).
m is a float and e is an int, such that x = m * 2.**e.
If x is 0, m and e are both 0.  Else 0.5 <= abs(m) < 1.0.
children.name: frexp

children.docstring:
fsum(iterable)

Return an accurate floating point sum of values in the iterable.
Assumes IEEE-754 floating point arithmetic.
children.name: fsum

children.docstring:
hypot(x, y)

Return the Euclidean distance, sqrt(x*x + y*y).
children.name: hypot

children.docstring:
isinf(x) -> bool

Check if float x is infinite (positive or negative).
children.name: isinf

children.docstring:
isnan(x) -> bool

Check if float x is not a number (NaN).
children.name: isnan

children.docstring:
lgamma(x)

children.name: lgamma

children.docstring:
log(x[, base])

Return the logarithm of x to the given base.

children.name: log

children.docstring:
log10(x)

Return the base 10 logarithm of x.
children.name: log10

children.docstring:
log1p(x)

Return the natural logarithm of 1+x (base e).
The result is computed in a way which is accurate for x near zero.
children.name: log1p

children.docstring:
modf(x)

Return the fractional and integer parts of x.  Both results carry the sign
of x and are floats.
